<DOC><DOCNO> WSJ881006-0187 </DOCNO><HL> Union Texas Unit Paid $21 Million By Insurers For Oil Platform Blast </HL><SO> </SO><CO> UTH </CO><IN> PET INS </IN><DATELINE> HOUSTON  </DATELINE><TEXT>   Union Texas Petroleum Holdings Inc. said a unit received $21 million from insurers to cover lost production from the Piper Alpha oil platform, which exploded in the North Sea in July.    The unit, Union Texas Petroleum Ltd., has a 20% interest in the platform. The payment represents business interruption losses through Sept. 30. The company has $275 million or 36 months, whichever comes first, of business interruption coverage.    Union Texas, an independent oil and gas producer, earlier received $127.8 million from its insurers for property damages to the platform. Union Texas also has $70 million of well-control and redrilling coverage, as well as third-party liability pollution and platform removal coverage.    Occidental Petroleum Corp. was operator of the platform.    In New York Stock Exchange composite trading yesterday, Union Texas shares closed at $9.75, down 25 cents. </TEXT></DOC>